Hisce quatuor malis opponit Logica totidem remedia. Definitio exhibet menti essentiam rerum: divisio efficit cognitionem distinctam: syllogismus tollit animi incertitudinem et errorem circa themata complexa: methodus ἀταξίαν sive confusionem.” Hence it appears that falsity of judgment simply was not regarded as remediable by Legio, but only falsity in relation to the syllogism, i. e. so far as it depends on the assumed truth or falsity of other judgments. But the above statement requires considerable limitation. Every process of thought is liable to a formal defect as violating its own laws‚ and to amalarici desem, as inconsistent with experience. Thus aconcept may be obscure or indis- tinct fonnally, as implying attributes which cannot be thought in conjunctim, as when its different parts contradict one another: a judgment may be formally salse, for the sarno reason: and a reasoning may bc formally inconsequentes transgressing the laws of the syllogism. In all these cases the fault may be detected by Logic. On the other hand, a concept may bc materially obscure or indistinct‚ as containing attributes which we have never met with in our own expe rience: ajudgment may be materially false, as being at varianae with facts: a reasoning may bc materially incon· sequent, as not warranted by the laws or analogias of nature.
